bi harps to the European J. S. Bach revival, music expressed elemental truths in the nineteenth century. Creatures of the Air tells these truths through stories about suffocation and breathing, architecture and environmental design, climate strife, and racial turmoil. Contributing to elemental media studies, the energy humanities, and colonial histories, Davies shows how music, no longer just an innocent luxury, is implicated in the struggle for control over air as a precious natural resource. What emerges is a complex political ecology of the global nineteenth century and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAir. 0aEcomusicology. 0aEthnomusicologyzGabonxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusic and technologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicxEnvironmental aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicxSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aMusicxSocial aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aRespiration. 0aSingingxHistoryy19th century. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh  amusic studies, environmental humanities, elemental media studies, anthropocene, humanitarian reason, colonial modernity, race and biopolitics, music analysis, equatorialism, poiesis and creativity studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079732940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226826141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226826141/original  a978-3-11-079732-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles